  "prompt": "How is the formula for average acceleration determined?",
  "response": "The formula for average acceleration is derived from the basic definition of acceleration, which is the rate at which an object's velocity changes over time. Here's a step-by-step explanation of how the formula for average acceleration is determined:\n\n1. **Definition of Acceleration:**\n   - Acceleration (\\(a\\)) is the rate of change of velocity (\\(\\Delta v\\)) with respect to time (\\(\\Delta t\\)).\n   - Mathematically, this can be expressed as:\n     \\[\n     a = \\frac{\\Delta v}{\\Delta t}\n     \\]\n   \n2. **Change in Velocity:**\n   - The change in velocity (\\(\\Delta v\\)) is the difference between the final velocity (\\(v_f\\)) and the initial velocity (\\(v_i\\)).\n   - Therefore, \\(\\Delta v = v_f - v_i\\).\n\n3. **Change in Time:**\n   - The change in time (\\(\\Delta t\\)) is the difference between the final time (\\(t_f\\)) and the initial time (\\(t_i\\)).\n   - Therefore, \\(\\Delta t = t_f - t_i\\).\n\n4. **Combining the Definitions:**\n   - Substituting the expressions for \\(\\Delta v\\) and \\(\\Delta t\\) into the definition of acceleration, we get:\n     \\[\n     a = \\frac{v_f - v_i}{t_f - t_i}\n     \\]\n   - This is the formula for average acceleration.\n\n### Final Formula:\n\\[\n\\text{Average Acceleration} = \\frac{v_f - v_i}{t_f - t_i}\n\\]\n\n### Key Points:\n- **Average Acceleration** is a measure of how quickly the velocity of an object changes over a specific time interval.\n- The formula is derived directly from the definition of acceleration and involves the change in velocity and the change in time.\n- In vector form, acceleration can also include direction, but the scalar form (as shown above) gives the magnitude of average acceleration.\n\nThis formula is fundamental in kinematics and is widely used in physics to analyze motion.",
